const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'What is retainage in construction?',
    answer:
      'Retainage (also called retention) is a percentage of each progress payment that the owner or general contractor withholds until the project reaches substantial completion or another milestone defined in the contract. It acts as a financial guarantee that the work will be finished and defects corrected before the final dollar is released.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How much retainage is typical on a construction project?',
    answer:
      '10% is the most common rate on commercial work. Some contracts reduce the rate to 5% once the project hits 50% completion — this is often called variable retainage or a step-down. Specialty trade contracts sometimes start at 5%. Whatever the rate, it is defined in your subcontract, so read that clause carefully before signing.',
  },
  {
    question: 'When is retainage released?',
    answer:
      'Release timing is set by the contract. Most contracts release retainage at substantial completion — when the work is complete enough that the owner can use it for its intended purpose. Final release often requires a signed lien waiver from the subcontractor. Some contracts hold a portion until the punchlist is fully resolved.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the difference between pay-when-paid and pay-if-paid for retainage?',
    answer:
      'Pay-when-paid means the GC must pay you within a reasonable time after receiving payment from the owner — it shifts timing, not the obligation to pay. Pay-if-paid attempts to shift the entire financial risk: the GC only owes you if the owner pays first. Many states limit or prohibit pay-if-paid clauses. Know which applies in your state before signing a subcontract.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How does BuildWorkPro track retainage on pay applications?',
    answer:
      'Every pay application in BuildWorkPro has a Retainage % field that defaults to 10% and can be adjusted per pay app to match your contract terms. The payment application summary shows the retainage withheld for that period, so the net amount due reflects the holdback. BuildWorkPro produces AIA-style progress billing documents — not the copyrighted AIA G702/G703 forms themselves.',
  },
];
---

<Layout
  title="Retainage in Construction: How It Works | BuildWorkPro"
  description="Construction retainage is the percentage withheld from each pay application until project closeout. Learn how it works, typical rates, and how to track your holdback."
>
  <Header />
  <main class="pt-32 pb-20">
    <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="mb-12">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-brand-600 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">Blog</p>
        <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-extrabold text-slate-900 tracking-tight leading-tight">
          Retainage in Construction: How It Works and How to Track It
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-slate-400">Published June 12, 2026 · 8 min read</p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-headings:font-semibold prose-headings:tracking-tight prose-a:text-brand-600"
      >
        <p>
          Retainage is the line on every pay application that never gets paid — until it does. When
          a general contractor withholds 10% of each progress payment, that money doesn't disappear.
          It accumulates across every billing period until the job reaches closeout, and then — if
          the paperwork is in order and the contract terms are met — it comes back to you.
        </p>
        <p>
          Subcontractors who don't understand how retainage works get blindsided by cash-flow gaps
          that should have been planned for. This guide explains what retainage is, how it compounds
          over a project's life, when it's released, and how to keep an accurate running balance so
          nothing gets left on the table.
        </p>

        <div class="rounded-xl bg-slate-50 border border-slate-100 p-6 not-prose my-8">
          <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-3">Key takeaways</h2>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-600 list-disc pl-5">
            <li>
              Retainage is a contractual holdback — commonly 10% — withheld from each progress
              payment until a defined project milestone.
            </li>
            <li>
              It accumulates across every billing period and can total a significant sum by the end
              of a long job.
            </li>
            <li>
              The rate and release conditions are set in your subcontract — read that section before
              signing.
            </li>
            <li>
              Variable retainage (the rate drops at 50% completion) is worth negotiating on larger
              projects.
            </li>
            <li>
              Track your running retainage balance on every pay app so you know exactly what you're
              owed and when to expect it.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h2>What is retainage?</h2>
        <p>
          Retainage (sometimes called retention in contract language) is a percentage of each
          progress payment that the owner or general contractor holds back until the project reaches
          a specified milestone — typically substantial completion. Think of it as collateral: the
          owner keeps a portion of what you've earned to ensure the work gets finished and defects
          get corrected before the final dollar is released.
        </p>
        <p>
          For subcontractors on a GC contract, the most common retainage rate on commercial work is
          10%. On every pay application, that withheld 10% compounds across billing periods. By the
          time you've billed 90% of a $400,000 contract, retainage is holding $36,000 of money
          you've already earned and paid your crew for.
        </p>
        <p>
          Retainage isn't unique to subcontractors — the GC faces the same holdback from the owner.
          But because subs are further down the payment chain, the cash-flow impact lands harder.
        </p>

        <h2>How much retainage is typical?</h2>
        <p>
          10% is the standard on most commercial subcontracts. A few situations where you'll see
          different rates:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Variable retainage.</strong> Some contracts reduce the rate from 10% to 5% once the
            project is 50% complete. This is a common concession on larger or longer jobs and worth asking
            for — it meaningfully improves cash flow in the back half of the project.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Specialty trades.</strong> HVAC, electrical, and plumbing work is often front-loaded:
            rough-in happens early and trim-out happens near the end, so a flat 10% holdback can be disproportionate.
            Some specialty subcontracts negotiate a 5% rate from the start.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Public work.</strong> Government contracts and public projects may cap retainage by
            statute — sometimes at 5% — with different step-down rules. Know the rules that govern your
            type of work.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Whatever rate applies, it is written in your subcontract. Read the payment, retainage, and
          payment-conditions sections before you sign or mobilize. That's also where the release
          conditions live.
        </p>

        <h2>How retainage accumulates over a project</h2>
        <p>
          The math is straightforward, but the dollar amounts surprise people. On a six-period
          project with a $500,000 contract and 10% retainage:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Period 1 — bill $80,000, receive $72,000; retainage held: $8,000</li>
          <li>Period 2 — bill $90,000, receive $81,000; retainage held to date: $17,000</li>
          <li>Period 3 — bill $95,000, receive $85,500; retainage held to date: $26,500</li>
          <li>Period 4 — bill $85,000, receive $76,500; retainage held to date: $35,000</li>
          <li>Period 5 — bill $80,000, receive $72,000; retainage held to date: $43,000</li>
          <li>Period 6 — bill $70,000, receive $63,000; retainage held to date: $50,000</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          By the time you've fully billed the contract, $50,000 is sitting in holdback. That's
          working capital you've spent on labor and materials but can't access until closeout. On a
          project that runs twelve or eighteen months, the timing of that release becomes a
          significant line item in your cash-flow forecast.
        </p>

        <h2>When is retainage released?</h2>
        <p>
          Release timing is defined in the contract — there is no universal rule. Common release
          triggers:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Substantial completion.</strong> The most common trigger. Substantial completion is
            the point where the work is complete enough that the owner can occupy and use the space for
            its intended purpose, even if a punchlist remains. Push your contract to define this concretely
            (tied to a signed certificate or an agreed inspection) rather than leaving it open to interpretation.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Punchlist completion.</strong> Some contracts hold back a portion — sometimes twice
            the value of remaining punchlist items — until the list is fully resolved. Know whether your
            contract uses a single release event or a two-step release.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Required paperwork.</strong> Final retainage release commonly requires a signed lien
            waiver, a final invoice, or a certificate of substantial completion. Have those documents
            ready before you request release.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          One more wrinkle: your retainage release often flows down from the owner's release to the
          GC. If the owner is slow — or disputes something — the GC may hold your retainage even
          after your work is complete. This depends on whether your subcontract contains a
          <strong>pay-when-paid</strong> or <strong>pay-if-paid</strong> clause. Pay-when-paid shifts
          the timing; pay-if-paid attempts to shift the entire obligation. Many states limit or prohibit
          pay-if-paid language. Know which applies to you.
        </p>

        <h2>Tracking retainage on your pay applications</h2>
        <p>
          Every{' '}
          <a href="/blog/aia-pay-application-guide/">AIA-style pay application</a> should show, for each
          period:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>The amount billed this period</li>
          <li>The retainage withheld this period</li>
          <li>The total retainage withheld to date (across all prior pay apps)</li>
          <li>The net amount due after retainage</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          The{' '}
          <a href="/blog/schedule-of-values-guide/">schedule of values</a> is what makes this possible
          — each line carries a running balance of what's been billed, what's been stored, and what's
          been withheld, period by period. A well-maintained SOV makes the final retainage balance easy
          to verify and hard to dispute.
        </p>
        <p>
          In BuildWorkPro, retainage is tracked on every{' '}
          <a href="/features/pay-applications/">pay application</a>. The Retainage % field defaults
          to 10% and adjusts per pay app to match your contract terms. The payment application
          summary shows the retainage withheld for that period, so the net amount due reflects the
          actual holdback — not a number someone hand-calculated on a spreadsheet:
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="my-10">
        <DemoVideo
          src="/videos/pay-app-demo.mp4"
          poster="/videos/pay-app-demo-poster.jpg"
          label="Demo: a BuildWorkPro pay application showing the retainage field, schedule of values billing, and payment application summary with retainage withheld"
