      <div
        class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-headings:font-semibold prose-headings:tracking-tight prose-a:text-brand-600"
      >
        <h2>Retainage on change orders</h2>
        <p>
          Approved change orders increase the contract sum — and unless your contract says
          otherwise, retainage applies to those amounts too. A $20,000 change order with 10%
          retainage means $18,000 now and $2,000 at closeout, just like the base contract.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is another reason to keep your{' '}
          <a href="/features/change-orders/">change orders</a> current and approved before you bill them.
          An unapproved change order billed on a pay app creates both a retainage exposure and a payment
          dispute. In BuildWorkPro, the change orders total on a pay app prefills from approved change
          orders only — so the contract value on your billing reflects what's actually been authorized.
        </p>

        <h2>Common retainage problems for subcontractors</h2>
        <p>
          Retainage disputes are among the most common payment problems in construction. A few to
          watch for:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>GC holds retainage past substantial completion.</strong> A common tactic: keeping
            your funds open by citing a punchlist item you've already completed. Document punchlist completion
            dates in writing and get sign-off when items are resolved. That paper trail is what pushes
            the release.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Back-charges applied against retainage.</strong> Some GCs apply disputed back-charges
            directly against your retainage balance rather than resolving them separately. Know what your
            contract says about how back-charges are documented, disputed, and offset before a dollar
            disappears from your holdback.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>No tracking means no visibility.</strong> Subcontractors who don't track retainage
            per job sometimes miss the release entirely — the project closes, the GC sends a check, and
            no one notices if the amount is short. Set a reminder tied to your anticipated substantial
            completion date and reconcile the full retainage balance against what you receive.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Owner or GC financial trouble.</strong> If the owner runs into problems, your retainage
            is at risk along with everything else. In most states subcontractors can file a mechanics
            lien that covers retainage — understand your lien rights and deadlines early, not when there's
            already a problem.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>The bottom line</h2>
        <p>
          Retainage is a planned cash-flow gap, not a surprise. If you know the rate going in, track
          the running balance on every pay application, and know the exact conditions for release,
          you can manage it. The mistakes happen when retainage is treated as an afterthought and
          the final payment lands short with no clear record of what should have been there.
        </p>
        <p>
          Read the retainage clause before you sign the subcontract. Track it on every pay app.
          Document your work at closeout. Those three habits keep the holdback from becoming a
          dispute.
        </p>
      </div>

